    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "Kroll, Wemp, Hindson, Dobson, Freerksen, Schrader, Towns, Jantz, and Willmington couldn\u2019t find a croquet ball in the bathroom sink.\nVerse\n10. Five questions are asked. The first is, \u201cWhen are you going to get smart\u201d? (The New Authorized New Revised New International New Living New Standard New Bible). The second question is, \u201cIf God can construct a human ear, do you think He isn\u2019t capable of hearing\u201d? The third question is, \u201cIf He could construct a marvel like the human eye, do you think He is blind\u201d? The fourth question is, \u201cWon\u2019t God correct His own people if He takes time out to correct the heathen\u201d? And the last question is, \u201cSince God imparted to man the ability to think, do you think that He doesn\u2019t know what is going on inside your head\u201d? (\u201cThe Lord knoweth the thoughts of man, that they are vanity\u201d vs. 11).\nVerse\n10. Kroll\u2019s proclivity for playing the dumbbell is obvious, for before\nverse 10 he says that the \u201coffering\u201d of\n10. Is this prayer [v_Rom_11_8] much worse than the one recorded in Romans 11:8\u20139 under \u201cthe covenant of Grace\u201d (to cite the \u201cHoly Joes\u201d)? David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2014quoted nearly thirty years after the Resurrection of the \u201csuffering Saviour\u201d\u2014is praying for the damnation of every Christ rejector in his own nation. No wonder Jerry Falwell and his staff have such a time with the Psalm! Grace is not for those who reject grace. Mercy is not for those who reject mercy. Forgiveness doesn\u2019t apply to any man who doesn\u2019t need, or want, forgiveness. If a sinner doesn\u2019t need mercy, why ask for it? If God is merciful to everyone, regardless of their attitude towards His Righteousness, what is the point in praying [v_Luk_18_13] \u201cGod be merciful to me a sinner\u201d (Luke 18:13)? Why, there wouldn\u2019t be any. The man described in this Psalm is not a vicious, depraved, degenerate \u201chell cat\u201d who sees his need of salvation and cries out to God for it (as we just [v_Psa_109_6] saw in Ps. 109:6, 13, 19, and 28). No, this man is a proud, arrogant, cruel blasphemer who has no intention of seeking mercy or grace, or asking for either. This is the [v_Job_41_24] one whose heart is as hard as a \u201cmillstone\u201d (Job 41:24), [v_Job_41_33] and who is \u201cmade without fear\u201d (Job 41:33). Note the [v_Job_41_1] context is \u201cleviathan\u201d (Job 41:1, whom Kroll and his buddies shrunk down to a \u201ccrocodile\u201d with the approval of the translators of the ASV, NASV, RV, RSV, NRSV, and NIV). The `[group_Canaanites_Gen_10]` man in the spotlight of\nPsalm 109:",
    "Commentary Vol. 90": "Filled . The original word is of frequent occurrence, signifying to feed, to satisfy with food, original y used of feeding animals, in later Greek of feeding men. (Compare in Matthew 14:20, Luke 16:21; James 2:16; Philippians 4:12; Revelation 19:21) They who hunger and thirst for righteousness shal , under Messiah's reign, be fed full, completely satisfied. It of course does not mean satisfied once for all, so as to have no desire any more. That is here true which Wisdom says in Sirach (Ecclus.) Sirach 24:21, 'They that eat me shal still hunger, and they that drink me shal still thirst.' The Scriptures teach that this satisfaction will be progressive in the present life, and become perfect as we enter upon the perfect world.\u00e2\u20ac\u201dObserve (Tholuck) that after righteousness there fol ow three elements of righteousness, viz., pity, purity, peace. Matthew 5:",
    "Commentary Vol. 91": "Filled. The original word is of frequent occurrence, signifying to feed, to satisfy with food, originally used of feeding animals, in later Greek of feeding men. [v_Mat_14_20] (Compare in Matthew 14:20, Luke 16:21; James 2:16; Philippians 4:12; Revelation 19:21) They who hunger and thirst for righteousness shall, under Messiah's reign, be fed full, completely satisfied. It of course does not mean satisfied once for all, so as to have no desire any more. That is here true which Wisdom says in Sirach (Ecclus.) Sirach 24:21, 'They that eat me shall still hunger, and they that drink me shall still thirst.' The Scriptures teach that this satisfaction will be progressive in the present life, and become perfect as we enter upon the perfect world.\u00e2\u20ac\u201dObserve (Tholuck) that after righteousness there follow three elements of righteousness, viz., pity, purity, peace. [v_Mat_5_7] Matthew 5:"
