    "A New and Concise Bible Dictionary": "Dwellers on Earth. This is an emphatic expression in the Revelation characterising those that seek their portion on earth at the time when the Lord Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ is refused His rights in it: a great trial awaits them. Rev. 3:",
    "Craig S. Keener": "Davies and Allison 1988: 449 cite Plato Crit. 120E; Rep. 2.375C; Lucian Somnium 10; Ep. Arist. 257, 263; Philo Vit. Mos. 2.279; Jos. Ant. 19.330.\n23. Cf. also the threefold division in Lk 24:44 (more popular among the sages \u2014 Sirach prologue; ARN 14A: b. \u2019Abod. Zar. 19b; B. Bat `[animal_Bat_Lev_11]`. 13b, bar.; B. Qam. 92b; Mak. 10b; Sanh. 90b, Gamaliel II; 106a; p. Meg. 1:5, \u00a73; Ned. 3:9, \u00a73; Pesiq. Rab Kah. 12:13; Gen. Rab. 76:5; cf. Philo Vit. Con. 25). For weekly readings from both law and prophets in the second century, cf. m. Meg. 4:1-\n6. Snodgrass 1996: 107 suggests that \" prophets \" here qualifies law with a prophetic reading, as in 9:13; in this context it might also encourage persecuted disciples that the fruit of their labor would endure (5:12).",
    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "will be fulfilled [v_2Th_1_8] literally at the Second Advent (2 Thess. 1:8\u20139).\nPSALM 95 95:1 \u201cO come, let us sing unto the LORD: let us make a joyful noise to the rock of our salvation. 2 Let us come before his presence with thanksgiving, and make a joyful noise unto him with psalms. 3 For the LORD is a great God, and a great King above all gods. 4 In his hand are the deep places of the earth: the strength of the hills is his also. 5 The sea is his, and he made it: and his hands formed the dry land. 6 O come, let us worship and bow down: let us kneel before the LORD our maker. 7 For he is our God; and we are the people of his pasture, and the sheep of his hand. To day if ye will hear his voice, 8 Harden not your heart, as in the provocation, and as in the day of temptation in the wilderness: 9 When your fathers tempted me, proved me, and saw my work. 10 Forty years long was I grieved with this generation, and said, It is a people that do err in their heart, and they have not known my ways: 11 Unto whom I sware in my wrath that they should not enter into my rest.\u201d The verses are not in chronological order, much to the consternation of the Alexandrian Cult.\nVerses 1 through 6 are addressed to a Millennial saint who has survived Daniel\u2019s Seventieth Week and has held fast his [v_Heb_3_6] \u201cconfidence stedfast unto the end\u201d (Heb. 3:6, 14).\nVerses 7\u201311 are addressed to a Tribulation saint who [v_Mat_24_13] must \u201cendure unto the end\u201d (Matt. 24:13) and not [v_Heb_10_39] \u201cdraw back unto perdition\u201d (Heb. 10:39; see extensive comments on these dispensational matters in The `[object_Tabernacle_Heb_9]` Bible Believer\u2019s Commentary on Hebrews, 1989). There is an element of faith and works in the Tribulation that is not found in the Church Age, and no amount of \u201cgodly\u201d testimonies by \u201cgood, godly\u201d Baptists will ever alter that [v_Rev_12_11] Scriptural truth. The verses are: Revelation 12:11, 14:12; [v_Heb_3_5] Hebrews 3:5\u201319, 6:4\u20138, 10:26\u201331; Matthew 24:48\u201351, 25:1\u201330; etc. Inspirationally, we are to sing loudly when praising God (vss. 1\u20132). Twice we are told to make \u201ca joyful noise.\u201d We are to raise the roof; make a racket. The world never hesitates to do this when they worship their gods. Anyone who has ever attended a rock concert, a Miss America pageant, or a college football game knows what \u201ca joyful noise\u201d is. The shame of the saints is their low muttering of their hymns and their quiet, cool, level, calculated \u201cthanksgivings\u201d (vs. 2). The \u201cnoise\u201d is to be made \u201cwith psalms\u201d (vs. 2) in either Testament (see Col. 3:16), and this pretty well knocks the \u201canti- [v_Psa_92_3] instrumentalists\u201d (see Ps. 92:3 and comments) off the shelf. The Psalms prescribe noises made with \u201ctrumpet...psaltery and harp...timbrel and...stringed instruments and organs...loud cymbals...high [v_Psa_150_3] sounding cymbals\u201d (Ps. 150:3\u20135). Let me tell you, brother, an orchestra composed of those instruments is capable of making a loud noise. \u201cA great King above all gods\u201d (vs. 3). Look out! The last time you hit these \u201cgods,\u201d they were converted into Jewish magistrates (Ps. 82) by Liberty University and the other Alexandrian offshoots. \u201cNot that the heathen gods are realities...\u201d say Jamieson, Fausset, and Brown. But then when Jamieson, Fausset and Brown get to\nPsalm 97:7 they have a problem. There are the \u201cgods,\u201d and they are commanded to worship the one true God. Venema, back in the 1800s, had better sense. He said (Treasury, p. 170) that the reference was to angels \u201cwho are wont to be introduced absolutely under this name.\u201d Correct, and that was the key to\nPsalm 82, which Kroll couldn\u2019t handle. This time Kroll knows he is in a \u201csho nuff pickle,\u201d so he backs out gracefully with a quotation from Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]` Clarke (cited in The Treasury, p. 170) which doesn\u2019t explain one thing about the verse. Since he could have appealed to\n23. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` \u201cglory\u201d (vs. 3), that is to be declared, is NOT the gospel of the grace of God, nor is it the gospel of the Kingdom of Heaven, nor [v_Rom_2_16] what Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` calls \u201cmy gospel\u201d (Rom. 2:16), nor is it \u201cthe everlasting gospel\u201d which is preached in the last half of [v_Rev_14_6] the Tribulation (Rev. 14:6). The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` \u201cglory\u201d and the \u201cwonders\u201d that are to be declared among the people are that: \u201cthe LORD reigneth\u201d (vs. 10), \u201cThe `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` LORD made the heavens\u201d (vs. 5), and \u201che shall judge the people righteously\u201d (vs. 10). [v_Zec_13_3] Prophesying is \u201cout\u201d (see Zech. 13:3), and faith as a means of salvation is out, for the earth\u2019s inhabitants will [v_Jhn_20_29] all be in the shoes of Thomas Didymus (John `[char_John_Ref]` 20:29) who [v_Jhn_20_25] walked by sight, and not by faith (John `[char_John_Ref]` 20:25). (Some more Baptist spasms and sensational shocks for the apostate teachers at BBC and Liberty University!) The \u201cconstitution\u201d of this Millennial kingdom is given in Matthew 5\u2013"
